f England}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Dynasty, Norman}}\n[[Category:House of Normandy|Normandy]]\n[[Category:Viking Age in France]]\n[[Category:French noble families]]\n[[Category:English royal houses|Normandy]]\n[[Category:Royal houses of the County of Flanders|Normandy]]\n\n\n{{Normandy-stub}}\n{{UK-royal-stub}}\n", "name_user": "Anomalocaris", "label": "safe", "comment": "<small>...<small /> \u2192 <small>...</small>; unspaced en dash", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/House_of_Normandy"}
{"title_page": "Lord Alfred Paget", "text_new": "{{Use dmy dates|date=February 2017}}\n{{Use British English|date=February 2017}}\n[[File:Lord Alfred Paget, Vanity Fair, 1875-07-03,crop.jpg|thumb|Caricature by [[Carlo Pellegrini (caricaturist)|Ape]] published in [[Vanity Fair (British magazine 1868-1914)|Vanity Fair]] in 1875.]]\n'''Lord Alfred Henry Paget''' {{postnominals|country=GBR|size=100%|CB}} (26 June 1816 \u2013 24 August 1888<ref name=\"rayment\">{{Rayment-hc|l|2|date=March 2012}}</ref>) was a British soldier, courtier and [[Liberal Party (UK)|Liberal]] politician who sat in the [[House of Commons of the United Kingdom|House of Commons]] between 1837 and 1865.\n\n==Biography==\nPaget was the sixth son of the [[Henry William Paget, 1st Marquess of Anglesey|1st Marquess of Anglesey]]. He became a lieutenant in the [[Royal Horse Guards]]. In 1837 he was elected [[Member of Parliament]] for [[Lichfield (UK Parliament constituency)|Lichfield]] and held the seat until 1865,<ref name=\"rayment\" /> when he was defeated by the [[Conservative Party (UK)|Conservative]] [[Richard Dyott (died 1891)|Richard Dyott]].<ref name=\"craig1832-1885\">{{cite book\n |last=Craig\n |first=F. W. S.\n |authorlink= F. W. S. Craig\n |title=British parliamentary election results 1832\u20131885\n |origyear=1977\n |edition= 2nd\n |year=1989\n |publisher= Parliamentary Research Services\n |location=Chichester\n |isbn= 0-900178-26-4\n |pages=185\u2013186\n}}</ref>\n\nPaget was [[Chief Equerry and Clerk Marshal]] to [[Victoria of the United Kingdom|the Queen]] from July 1846 to March 1852, from December 1852 to March 1858, and from June 1859. The office ceased to be a political one from 1866.<ref>Chris Cook and Brendan Keith, ''British Historical Facts 1830-1900'', Macmillan 1975, p. 27</ref>\n\nHe was the Commodore of the [[Royal Thames Yacht Club]], 1846\u20131873, and Vice-Commodore, 1845-1846 and  1874\u20131888.<ref>[https://www.royalthames.com/About-RTYC/Royal-Thames-History/Flag-Officers-since-1775.]{{Dead link|date=March 2020 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref>\n\nOn 1 August 1874, he resigned the Chief Equerryship only.<ref>{{London Gazette|issue=24121|page=3965|date=11 August 1874}}</ref> He became a [[Lieutenant-Colonel]] (unattached) in 1854. He lived at  42 [[Grosvenor Place]], London, and at [[Melford Hall]], [[Sudbury, Suffolk]].\n\nHe died in 1888 unexpectedly, on his yacht off [[Inverness]].<ref name=\"Obituary\">{{cite news|title=The North Wales Chronicle and Advertiser for the Principality|url=http://newspapers.library.wales/view/4453829/4453837|accessdate=27 April 2018|date=1888-09-01}}</ref>\n\n== Business interests ==\nPaget was a director of the [[North Staffordshire Railway]] Company between January 1854 and February 1875.\n\n==Family==\nPaget married Cecilia, second daughter and co-heiress of George Thomas Wyndham, of [[Cromer Hall]], [[Norfolk]] in 1847. Their children were:\n\n*Victoria Alexandrina Paget (21 Apr 1848 \u2013 2 Feb 1859)\n*Evelyn Cecilia Paget (16 Jul 1849 \u2013 17 May 1904)\n*[[Arthur Paget (British Army officer)|Sir Arthur Henry Fitzroy Paget]] (1 Mar 1851 \u2013 8 Dec 1928)\n*Alfred Wyndham Paget (26 Mar 1852 \u2013 17 Jun 1918)\n*George Thomas Cavendish Paget (24 May 1853 \u2013 28 Jan 1939), raised [[Paget's Horse]] for service in the Boer War\n*Gerald Cecil Stewart Paget (15 Oct 1854 \u2013 25 Oct 1913), grandfather of [[Percy Bernard, 5th Earl of Bandon]].\n*Violet Mary Paget (1 Mar 1856 \u2013 13 Jun 1908)\n*[[Sydney Paget|Sydney Augustus Paget]] (19 Apr 1857 \u2013 16 Sep 1916)\n*Amy Olivia Paget (3 Jun 1858 \u2013 14 Feb 1948)\n*Alberta Victoria Paget (1859 \u2013 28 Jul 1945)\n*[[Almeric Hugh Paget, 1st Baron Queenborough]] (14 Mar 1861 \u2013 22 Sep 1949)\n*Alice Maud Paget (9 Jul 1862 \u2013 24 Dec 1925)\n*Alexandra Harriet Paget (31 Mar 1863 \u2013 1944), married [[Edward Colebrooke, 1st Baron Colebrooke]].\n*Guinevere Eva Paget (16 Mar 1869 \u2013 26 Feb 1894)\n\n== Cultural depictions ==\nIn the television series ''[[Victoria (UK TV series)|Victoria]]'', Lord Alfred is played by [[Jordan Waller]]. In the second series, he was depicted having a same-sex romantic relationship with Sir Robert Peel's secretary, [[Edward Drummond]]. There is no historical evidence that this took place. In the same series, Lord Alfred marries Lady Wilhelmina Coke (the niece of the Duchess of Buccleuch); but in real life, Lord Alfred married Cecilia Wyndham.<ref>Cecilia Wyndham. Ancestry.com. https://www.ancestry.co.uk/genealogy/records/cecilia-wyndham-24-12v9j2r?geo_a=r&geo_s=uk&geo_t=uk&geo_v=2.0.0&o_iid=41012&o_lid=41012&o_sch=Web+Property</ref>\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n* {{Hansard-contribs | lord-alfred-paget | Lord Alfred Paget }}\n\n{{s-start}}\n{{s-par|uk}}\n{{succession box\n | before  = [[Sir Edward Scott, 2nd Baronet|Sir Edward Scott, Bt]]\n | before2 = [[George Anson (British Army general)|Sir George Anson]]\n | title = [[Member of Parliament]] for [[Lichfield (UK Parliament constituency)|Lichfield]]\n | years = [[1837 United Kingdom general election|1837]]\u2013[[1865 United Kingdom general election|1865]]\n | with  = [[George Anson (British Army general)|Sir George Anson]] to 1841\n | with2 = [[Granville Leveson-Gower, 2nd Earl Granville|Lord Levson]] 1841\u20131846\n | with3 = [[Edward Lloyd-Mostyn, 2nd Baron Mostyn|Edward Lloyd-Mostyn]] 1846\u20131847\n | with4 = [[Thomas Anson, 2nd Earl of Lichfield|Viscount Anson]] 1847\u20131854\n | with5 = [[Henry Cavendish, 3rd Baron Waterpark|Lord Waterpark]] 1854\u20131856\n | with6 = [[Dudley Ryder, 3rd Earl of Harrowby|Viscount Sandon]] 1856\u20131859\n | with7 = [[Augustus Anson]] from 1859\n\n | after  = [[Richard Dyott (died 1891)|Richard Dyott]]\n | after2 = [[Augustus Anson]]\n}}\n{{s-court}}\n{{succession box|title=[[Chief Equerry and Clerk Marshal]]|years=1846\u20131852|after=[[Charles Colville, 1st Viscount Colville of Culross|The Lord Colville of Culross]]|before=[[Lord Charles Wellesley]]\n}}\n{{succession box|title=[[Chief Equerry and Clerk Marshal]]|years=1852\u20131858|after=[[Charles Colville, 1st Viscount Colville of Culross|The Lord Colville of Culross]]|before=[[Charles Colville, 1st Viscount Colville of Culross|The Lord Colville of Culross]]\n}}\n{{succession box|title=[[Chief Equerry and Clerk Marshal]]|years=1859\u20131874|after=[[John Carstairs McNeill]]|before=[[Charles Colville, 1st Viscount Colville of Culross|The Lord Colville of Culross]]\n}}\n{{s-end}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Paget, Alfred}}\n[[Category:1816 births]]\n[[Category:1888 deaths]]\n[[Category:Companions of the Order of the Bath]]\n[[Category:Royal Horse Guards officers]]\n[[Category:Liberal Party (UK) MPs for English constituencies]]\n[[Category:Younger sons of marquesses]]\n[[Category:UK MPs 1837\u20131841]]\n[[Category:UK MPs 1841\u20131847]]\n[[Category:UK MPs 1847\u20131852]]\n[[Category:UK MPs 1852\u20131857]]\n[[Category:UK MPs 1857\u20131859]]\n[[Category:UK MPs 1859\u20131865]]\n[[Category:People from Long Melford]]\n[[Category:Equerries]]\n[[Category:Paget family|Alfred]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use dmy dates|date=February 2017}}\n{{Use British English|date=February 2017}}\n[[File:Lord Alfred Paget, Vanity Fair, 1875-07-03,crop.jpg|thumb|Caricature by [[Carlo Pellegrini (caricaturist)|Ape]] published in [[Vanity Fair (British magazine 1868-1914)|Vanity Fair]] in 1875.]]\n'''Lord Alfred Henry Paget''' {{postnominals|country=GBR|size=100%|CB}} (26 June 1816 \u2013 24 August 1888<ref name=\"rayment\">{{Rayment-hc|l|2|date=March 2012}}</ref>) was a British soldier, courtier and [[Liberal Party (UK)|Liberal]] politician who sat in the [[House of Commons of the United Kingdom|House of Commons]] between 1837 and 1865.\n\n==Biography==\nPaget was the sixth son of the [[Henry William Paget, 1st Marquess of Anglesey|1st Marquess of Anglesey]]. He became a lieutenant in the [[Royal Horse Guards]]. In 1837 he was elected [[Member of Parliament]] for [[Lichfield (UK Parliament constituency)|Lichfield]] and held the seat until 1865,<ref name=\"rayment\" /> when he was defeated by the [[Conservative Party (UK)|Conservative]] [[Richard Dyott (died 1891)|Richard Dyott]].<ref name=\"craig1832-1885\">{{cite book\n |last=Craig\n |first=F. W. S.\n |authorlink= F. W. S. Craig\n |title=British parliamentary election results 1832\u20131885\n |origyear=1977\n |edition= 2nd\n |year=1989\n |publisher= Parliamentary Research Services\n |location=Chichester\n |isbn= 0-900178-26-4\n |pages=185\u2013186\n}}</ref>\n\nPaget was [[Chief Equerry and Clerk Marshal]] to [[Victoria of the United Kingdom|the Queen]] from July 1846 to March 1852, from December 1852 to March 1858, and from June 1859. The office ceased to be a political one from 1866.<ref>Chris Cook and Brendan Keith, ''British Historical Facts 1830-1900'', Macmillan 1975, p. 27</ref>\n\nHe was the Commodore of the [[Royal Thames Yacht Club]], 1846-1873, and Vice-Commodore, 1845-1846 and  1874-1888.<ref>[https://www.royalthames.com/About-RTYC/Royal-Thames-History/Flag-Officers-since-1775.]{{Dead link|date=March 2020 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref>\n\nOn 1 August 1874, he resigned the Chief Equerryship only.<ref>{{London Gazette|issue=24121|page=3965|date=11 August 1874}}</ref> He became a [[Lieutenant-Colonel]] (unattached) in 1854. He lived at  42 [[Grosvenor Place]], London, and at [[Melford Hall]], [[Sudbury, Suffolk]].\n\nHe died in 1888 unexpectedly, on his yacht off [[Inverness]].<ref name=\"Obituary\">{{cite news|title=The North Wales Chronicle and Advertiser for the Principality|url=http://newspapers.library.wales/view/4453829/4453837|accessdate=27 April 2018|date=1888-09-01}}</ref>\n\n== Business interests ==\nPaget was a director of the [[North Staffordshire Railway]] Company between January 1854 and February 1875.\n\n==Family==\nPaget married Cecilia, second daughter and co-heiress of George Thomas Wyndham, of [[Cromer Hall]], [[Norfolk]] in 1847. Their children were:\n\n*Victoria Alexandrina Paget (21 Apr 1848 \u2013 2 Feb 1859)\n*Evelyn Cecilia Paget (16 Jul 1849 \u2013 17 May 1904)\n*[[Arthur Paget (British Army officer)|Sir Arthur Henry Fitzroy Paget]] (1 Mar 1851 \u2013 8 Dec 1928)\n*Alfred Wyndham Paget (26 Mar 1852 \u2013 17 Jun 1918)\n*George Thomas Cavendish Paget (24 May 1853 \u2013 28 Jan 1939), raised [[Paget's Horse]] for service in the Boer War\n*Gerald Cecil Stewart Paget (15 Oct 1854 \u2013 25 Oct 1913), grandfather of [[Percy Bernard, 5th Earl of Bandon]].\n*Violet Mary Paget (1 Mar 1856 \u2013 13 Jun 1908)\n*[[Sydney Paget|Sydney Augustus Paget]] (19 Apr 1857 \u2013 16 Sep 1916)\n*Amy Olivia Paget (3 Jun 1858 \u2013 14 Feb 1948)\n*Alberta Victoria Paget (1859 \u2013 28 Jul 1945)\n*[[Almeric Hugh Paget, 1st Baron Queenborough]] (14 Mar 1861 \u2013 22 Sep 1949)\n*Alice Maud Paget (9 Jul 1862 \u2013 24 Dec 1925)\n*Alexandra Harriet Paget (31 Mar 1863 \u2013 1944), married [[Edward Colebrooke, 1st Baron Colebrooke]].\n*Guinevere Eva Paget (16 Mar 1869 \u2013 26 Feb 1894)\n\n== Cultural depictions ==\nIn the television series ''[[Victoria (UK TV series)|Victoria]]'', Lord Alfred is played by [[Jordan Waller]]. In the second series, he was depicted having a same-sex romantic relationship with Sir Robert Peel's secretary, [[Edward Drummond]]. There is no historical evidence that this took place. In the same series, Lord Alfred marries Lady Wilhelmina Coke (the niece of the Duchess of Buccleuch); but in real life, Lord Alfred married Cecilia Wyndham.<ref>Cecilia Wyndham. Ancestry.com. https://www.ancestry.co.uk/genealogy/records/cecilia-wyndham-24-12v9j2r?geo_a=r&geo_s=uk&geo_t=uk&geo_v=2.0.0&o_iid=41012&o_lid=41012&o_sch=Web+Property</ref>\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n* {{Hansard-contribs | lord-alfred-paget | Lord Alfred Paget }}\n\n{{s-start}}\n{{s-par|uk}}\n{{succession box\n | before  = [[Sir Edward Scott, 2nd Baronet|Sir Edward Scott, Bt]]\n | before2 = [[George Anson 