52\u20131857]]\n[[Category:UK MPs 1857\u20131859]]\n[[Category:UK MPs 1859\u20131865]]\n[[Category:People from Long Melford]]\n[[Category:Equerries]]\n[[Category:Paget family|Alfred]]\n", "name_user": "Iridescent", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eBiography:Cleanup andtypo fixing,typo(s) fixed: 1846-1873 \u2192 1846\u20131873 (2)", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Lord_Alfred_Paget"}
{"title_page": "William Clements, 3rd Earl of Leitrim", "text_new": "[[File:William Clements, 3rd Earl of Leitrim.jpg|thumb|The 3rd Earl of Leitrim.]]\n'''William Sydney Clements, 3rd Earl of Leitrim''' (15 October 1806 \u2013 2 April 1878), was an [[Anglo-Irish people|Anglo-Irish]] nobleman and landlord notorious in Irish history for his mistreatment of his tenants. He was assassinated in the north of [[County Donegal]] in [[Ulster]] in April 1878.\n\nBorn in [[Dublin]], he was educated at the [[Royal Military College, Sandhurst|Sandhurst]] and was commissioned as an [[ensign (rank)|Ensign]] in the [[43rd Foot]] in 1824. In 1831 he was promoted [[Captain (British Army and Royal Marines)|Captain]], having served in [[Portugal]] between 1826 and 1827, and that same year was appointed an [[aide-de-camp]] to the [[Lord Lieutenant of Ireland]]. In 1835 he transferred to the [[51st Foot]]. In 1839, on the death of his elder brother, he became known as Viscount Clements and also succeeded his brother as a [[Member of Parliament]] for [[Leitrim (UK Parliament constituency)|County Leitrim]], a seat he held until 1847.\n\nOn his father's death in 1854, Clements succeeded as 3rd Earl. In 1855 he was promoted [[Lieutenant-Colonel]] and subsequently retired from the [[British Army]]. Over the next two decades, his overbearing behaviour as a landlord brought him much hatred from his tenants, [[Roman Catholic Church|Catholic]] and [[Protestant]] alike, whom he evicted with equal enthusiasm.  According to his biographer Fiona Slevin, Lord Leitrim was accused by some of \"repeatedly [violating] young girls and [claiming] ''[[droit du seigneur]]'' ... some of his peers repeated accusations of his 'immorality towards daughters of tenants' in the House of Commons and named him 'the bad earl'.\"  However, Slevin also quotes a journalist who investigated Lord Leitrim's assassination as claiming, \"'even among those who hold the strongest views upon Lord Leitrim's conduct as a landlord, the charge (of debauchery) is discredited and I did not meet a single person who regarded it as tenable.'\"  In Slevin's words, \"the final straw that motivated the individuals involved\" in Lord Leitrim's assassination was his alleged [[rape]] of the daughter of one of his assassins.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.loughrynn.net/id31.htm|title=William Sydney Clements, 3rd Earl of Leitrim (Lord Leitrim)|last=Slevin|first=Fiona|date=18 January 2014|website=Lough Rynn|access-date=12 March 2018}}</ref>\n\nLeitrim was deeply opposed to [[William Ewart Gladstone|Gladstone]]'s [[Irish Land Act]] of 1870 and was one of eight [[Peerage|peers]] to protest against the legislation when it reached the [[House of Lords]]. Among those he also quarrelled with were the [[Presbyterianism|Presbyterian]] minister of [[Milford, County Donegal|Milford]] in North Donegal, and the Lord Lieutenant himself, [[George William Frederick Howard, 7th Earl of Carlisle|The 7th Earl of Carlisle]], who removed him from his appointments as a [[justice of the peace]] for [[Counties of Ireland|Counties]] Leitrim, [[County Donegal|Donegal]], and [[County Galway|Galway]].\n\nIn April 1878, after surviving various attempts on his life, Lord Leitrim was assassinated, along with his clerk and driver, near Cratlagh Wood while on his way to Milford (a village he owned in its entirety) from his home, Manor Vaughan (usually known as Mulroy House), on Mulroy Bay. Michael Heraghty and brothers Thomas and Bernard McGranahan were arrested. \"The gun butt had been traced to Heraghty, and paper for the wadding used to load the rifle was traced to a school copybook owned by the McGranahans. The McGranahans were released from Lifford Jail due to a lack of evidence. Heraghty died in Lifford Jail of typhus... The assassins, Nial Shiels of Doughmore, an itinerant tailor, Michael Hergarty of Tullyconnell, and Michael McElwee of Ballyworiskey, were from the remote Fanad Peninsula. In 1877, \"McElwee's father was involved in litigation with Leitrim with the result that McElwee was rendered bankrupt, and his house and farm were sold at auction.\"<ref>Simonsen, Mary Lydon, ''A Murderer's Country, Joyce Country, Galway during Ireland's Land War - 1879-1882''</ref>\n\nLeitrim was buried in [[Dublin]] at [[St Michan's]] church, amid scenes of great agitation.<ref>{{Cite book|title=By hereditary virtues: a history of Lough Rynn|last=Slevin|first=Fiona|publisher=Coolabawn Publishing|year=2006|isbn=|location=Ireland|pages=}}</ref> \"The mob wanted to wreak their drunken rage on the dead body of the old Earl, as it was not enough that he had been murdered; and when they were disappointed in their charitable desire to throw the corpse into the street, they howled and yelled an accompaniment of brutal hate to the funeral service. It was a disgraceful affair, scarcely possible in any other latitude of the civilized world.\"<ref>\"Lord Leitrim,\" ''New York Tribune'', April 12, 1878</ref>\n\nA monument with a cross was set up at Kindrum in 1960 honoring McElwee, Shiels, and Michael Heraghty as the men whose actions \"Ended the tyranny of landlordism\".\n\nThe murder forms a major element in the plot of the 2005 play ''[[The Home Place]]'' by [[Brian Friel]].\n\n==Biography==\n* Dolan, Liam  ''The Third Earl of Leitrim'' (Fanad: James Shields, 1978)\n*{{cite book\n  | last = Malcolmson\n  | first = A.P.W.\n  | authorlink =\n  | coauthors =\n  | title = Virtues of a Wicked Earl: The Life and Legend of William Sydney Clements, 3rd Earl of Leitrim\n  | publisher = [[Four Courts Press]]\n  | year = 2008\n  | location = Dublin\n  | pages =\n  | url =\n  | doi =\n  | id =\n  | isbn = 978-1-84682-121-9}}\n*{{cite book\n  | last = Slevin\n  | first = Fiona\n  | authorlink =\n  | coauthors =\n  | title = By Hereditary Virtues: A History of Lough Rynn\n  | publisher = [http://www.loughrynn.net Coolabawn Publishing]\n  | year = 2006\n  | location = Dublin\n  | pages = 204\n  | doi =\n  | id =\n  | isbn = 0-9553883-0-9}}\n\n*{{cite book\n  | last = Simonsen\n  | first = Mary Lydon\n  | authorlink =\n  | coauthors =\n  | title = A Murderer's Country, Joyce Country Galway during Ireland's Land War - 1879-1882\n  | publisher = Quail Creek Publishing, LLC\n  | year = 2017\n  | location = Arizona\n  | pages =\n  | url =\n  | doi =\n  | id =\n  | isbn = 978-0692910610}}\n\n==Notes==\n{{reflist}}\n<<Dolan, photos on pages 116\u2013117.>>\n\n==External links==\n* [http://www.loughrynn.net/ A history of Lord Leitrim's life and times]\n*{{Rayment-hc|date=March 2012}}\n\n{{S-start}}\n{{s-par|uk}}\n{{s-bef | before = [[Robert Bermingham Clements|Robert Clements, Viscount Clements]] <br />[[Samuel White (Irish politician)|Samuel White]] }}\n{{s-ttl\n | title = [[Member of Parliament]] for [[Leitrim (UK Parliament constituency)|Leitrim]]\n | with  = [[Samuel White (Irish politician)|Samuel White]]\n | years = 1839 \u2013 [[1847 United Kingdom general election|1847]]\n}}\n{{s-aft|after=[[Edward King-Tenison]] <br /> [[Charles Clements (MP)|Charles Clements]] }}\n\n{{s-reg|ie}}\n{{succession box\n | title=[[Earl of Leitrim]]\n | years=1854 \u2013 1878\n | before=[[Nathaniel Clements, 2nd Earl of Leitrim|Nathaniel Clements]]\n | after=[[Robert Clements, 4th Earl of Leitrim|Robert Clements]]\n}}\n{{S-end}}\n\n{{Use dmy dates|date=January 2012}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Leitrim, William Clements, 3rd Earl of}}\n[[Category:1806 births|Leitrim, William Sydney Clements, 3rd Earl of]]\n[[Category:1878 deaths|Leitrim, William Sydney Clements, 3rd Earl of]]\n[[Category:43rd Regiment of Foot officers|Leitrim, William Sydney Clements, 3rd Earl of]]\n[[Category:Irish murder victims]]\n[[Category:King's Own Yorkshire Light Infantry officers|Leitrim, William Sydney Clements, 3rd Earl of]]\n[[Category:Members of the Parliament of the United Kingdom for County Leitrim constituencies (1801\u20131922)]]\n[[Category:People murdered in Ireland]]\n[[Category:Politicians from County Dublin]]\n[[Category:Politicians from County Leitrim]]\n[[Category:Graduates of the Royal Military College, Sandhurst]]\n[[Category:UK MPs 1837\u20131841]]\n[[Category:UK MPs 1841\u20131847]]\n[[Category:1870s murders in Ireland]]\n[[Category:Earls of Leitrim]]\n", "text_old": "[[File:William Clements, 3rd Earl of Leitrim.jpg|thumb|The 3rd Earl of Leitrim.]]\n'''William Sydney Clements, 3rd Earl of Leitrim''' (15 October 1806 \u2013 2 April 1878), was an [[Anglo-Irish people|Anglo-Irish]] nobleman and landlord notorious in Irish history for his mistreatment of his tenants. He was assassinated in the north of [[County Donegal]] in [[Ulster]] in April 1878.\n\nBorn in [[Dublin]], he was educated at the [[Royal Military College, Sandhurst|Sandhurst]] and was commissioned as an [[ensign (rank)|Ensign]] in the [[43rd Foot]] in 1824. In 1831 he was promoted [[Captain (British Army and Royal Marines)|Captain]], having served in [[Portugal]] between 1826 and 1827, and that same year was appointed an [[aide-de-camp]] to the [[Lord Lieutenant of Ireland]]. In 1835 he transferred to the [[51st Foot]]. In 1839, on the death of his elder brother, he became known as Viscount Clements and also succeeded his brother as a [[Member of Parliament]] for [[Leitrim (UK Parliament constituency)|County Leitrim]], a seat he held until 1847.\n\nOn his father's death in 1854, Clements succeeded as 3rd Earl. In 1855 he was promoted [[Lieutenant-Colonel]] and subsequently retired from the [[British Army]]. Over the next two decades, his overbearing behaviour as a landlord brought him much hatred from his tenants, [[Roman Catholic Church|Catholic]] and [[Protestant]] alike, whom he evicted with equal enthusiasm.  According to his biographer Fiona Slevin, Lord Leitrim was accused by some of \"repeatedly [violating] young girls and [claiming] ''[[droit du seigneur]]'' ... some of his peers repeated accusations of his 'immorality towards daughters of tenants' in the House of Commons and named him 'the bad earl'.\"  However, Slevin also quotes a journalist who investigated Lord Leitrim's assassination as claiming, \"'even among those who hold the strongest views upon Lord Leitrim's conduct as a landlord, the charge (of debauchery) is discredited and I did not meet a single person who regarded it as tenable.'\"  In Slevin's words, \"the final straw that motivated the individuals involved\" in Lord Leitrim's assassination was his alleged [[rape]] of the daughter of one of his assassins.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.loughrynn.net/id31.htm|title=William Sydney Clements, 3rd Earl of Leitrim (Lord Leitrim)|last=Slevin|first=Fiona|date=18 January 2014|website=Lough Rynn|access-date=12 March 2018}}</ref>\n\nLeitrim was deeply opposed to [[William Ewart Gladstone|Gladstone]]'s [[Irish Land Act]] of 1870 and was one of eight [[Peerage|peers]] to protest against the legislation when it reached the [[House of Lords]]. Among those he also quarrelled with were the [[Presbyterianism|Presbyterian]] minister of [[Milford, County Donegal|Milford]] in North Donegal, and the Lord Lieutenant himself, [[George William Frederick Howard, 7th Earl of Carlisle|The 7th Earl of Carlisle]], who removed him from his appointments as a [[justice of the peace]] for [[Counties of Ireland|Counties]] Leitrim, [[County Donegal|Donegal]], and [[County Galway|Galway]].\n\nIn April 1878, after surviving various attempts on his life, Lord Leitrim was assassinated, along with his clerk and driver, near Cratlagh Wood while on his way to Milford (a village he owned in its entirety) from his home, Manor Vaughan (usually known as Mulroy House), on Mulroy Bay. Michael Heraghty and brothers Thomas and Bernard McGranahan were arrested. \"The gun butt had been traced to Heraghty, and paper for the wadding used to load the rifle was traced to a school copybook owned by the McGranahans. The McGranahans were released from Lifford Jail due to a lack of evidence. Heraghty died in Lifford Jail of typhus... The assassins, Nial Shiels of Doughmore, an itinerant tailor, Michael Hergarty of Tullyconnell, and Michael McElwee of Ballyworiskey, were from the remote Fanad Peninsula. In 1877, \"McElwee's father was involved in litigation with Leitrim with the result that McElwee was rendered bankrupt, and his house and farm were sold at auction.\"<ref>Simonsen, Mary Lydon, ''A Murderer's Country, Joyce Country, Galway during Ireland's Land War - 1879-1882''</ref>\n\nLeitrim was buried in [[Dublin]] at [[St Michan's]] church, amid scenes of great agitation.<ref>{{Cite book|title=By hereditary virtues: a history of Lough Rynn|last=Slevin|first=Fiona|publisher=Coolabawn Publishing|year=2006|isbn=|location=Ireland|pages=}}</ref> \"The mob wanted to wreak their drunken rage on the dead body of the old Earl, as it was not enough that he had been murdered; and when they were disappointed in their charitable desire to throw the corpse into the street, they howled and yelled an accompaniment of brutal hate to the funeral service. It was a disgraceful affair, scarcely possible in any other latitude of the civilized world.\"<ref>\"Lord Leitrim,\" ''New York Tribune'', April 12, 1878</ref>\n\nA monument with a cross was set up at Kindrum in 1960 honoring McElwee, Shiels, and Michael Heraghty as the men whose actions \"Ended the tyranny of landlordism\".\n\nThe murder forms a major element in the plot of the 2005 play ''[[The Home Place]]'' by [[Brian Friel]].\n\n==Biography==\n* Dolan, Liam  ''The Third Earl of Leitrim'' (Fanad: James Shields, 1978)\n*{{cite book\n  | last = Malcolmson\n  | first = A.P.W.\n  | authorlink =\n  | coauthors =\n  | title = Virtues of a Wicked Earl: The Life and Legend of William Sydney Clements, 3rd Earl of Leitrim\n  | publisher = [[Four Courts Press]]\n  | year = 2008\n  | location = Dublin\n  | pages =\n  | url =\n  | doi =\n  | id =\n  | isbn = 978-1-84682-121-9}}\n*{{cite book\n  | last = Slevin\n  | first = Fiona\n  | authorlink =\n  | coauthors =\n  | title = By Hereditary Virtues: A History of Lough Rynn\n  | publisher = [http://www.loughrynn.net Coolabawn Publishing]\n  | year = 2006\n  | location = Dublin\n  | pages = 204\n  | doi =\n  | id =\n  | isbn = 0-9553883-0-9}}\n\n*{{cite book\n  | last = Simonsen\n  | first = Mary Lydon\n  | authorlink =\n  | coauthors =\n  | title = A Murderer's Country, Joyce Country Galway during Ireland's Land War - 1879-1882\n  | publisher = Quail Creek Publishing, LLC\n  | year = 2017\n  | location = Arizona\n  | pages =\n  | url =\n  | doi =\n  | id =\n  | isbn = 978-0692910610}}\n\n==Notes==\n{{reflist}}\n<<Dolan, photos on pages 116-117.>>\n\n==External links==\n* [http://www.loughrynn.net/ A history of Lord Leitrim's life and times]\n*{{Rayment-hc|date=March 2012}}\n\n{{S-start}}\n{{s-par|uk}}\n{{s-bef | before = [[Robert Bermingham Clements|Robert Clements, Viscount Clements]] <br />[[Samuel White (Irish politician)|Samuel White]] }}\n{{s-ttl\n | title = [[Member of Parliament]] for [[Leitrim (UK Parliament constituency)|Leitrim]]\n | with  = [[Samuel White (Irish politician)|Samuel White]]\n | years = 1839 \u2013 [[1847 United Kingdom general election|1847]]\n}}\n{{s-aft|after=[[Edward King-Tenison]] <br /> [[Charles Clements (MP)|Charles Clements]] }}\n\n{{s-reg|ie}}\n{{succession box\n | title=[[Earl of Leitrim]]\n | years=1854 \u2013 1878\n | before=[[Nathaniel Clements, 2nd Earl of Leitrim|Nathaniel Clements]]\n | after=[[Robert Clements, 4th Earl of Leitrim|Robert Clements]]\n}}\n{{S-end}}\n\n{{Use dmy dates|date=January 2012}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Leitrim, William Clements, 3rd Earl of}}\n[[Category:1806 births|Leitrim, William Sydney Clements, 3rd Earl of]]\n[[Category:1878 deaths|Leitrim, William Sydney Clements, 3rd Earl of]]\n[[Category:43rd Regiment of Foot officers|Leitrim, William Sydney Clements, 3rd Earl of]]\n[[Category:Irish murder victims]]\n[[Category:King's Own Yorkshire Light Infantry officers|Leitrim, William Sydney Clements, 3rd Earl of]]\n[[Category:Members of the Parliament of the United Kingd