{"title_page": "Richard Samuel Guinness", "text_new": "{{Use dmy dates|date=August 2016}}\n{{Use British English|date=August 2016}}\n'''Richard Samuel Guinness''' (7 June 1797 \u2013 27 August 1857) was an Irish lawyer and a [[Member of parliament#United Kingdom|Member of Parliament]].\n\n==Parents==\nRichard was the son of Richard Guinness (1755-1829), a Dublin barrister and judge, and his wife Mary Darley, descended from a well-known Dublin house-building family. He was a great-nephew of the brewer [[Arthur Guinness]].\n\nHis elder brother [[Robert Rundell Guinness]] (1789-1857) founded the [[Guinness Mahon]] merchant bank in 1836.\n\n==Career==\nRichard was called to the bar at the [[King's Inns]] in [[Dublin]] and practised as a [[barrister]].<ref>Burke, J. ''A Genealogical and Heraldic Dictionary of the Peerage and Baronetage of the British Empire'' (1839, Colburn, London p.645.</ref> He had a banking partnership with his elder brother Robert that ended in the 1830s. He then worked as a land agent, trading as \"R. Guinness & Co.\", but found it difficult in the aftermath of the [[Great Famine (Ireland)|Irish famine]] of the 1840s.\n\nHis election as MP for the [[Kinsale (UK Parliament constituency)|Kinsale division]] ended abruptly in early 1848. On a petition by the losing [[Liberal Party (UK)|Liberal]] candidate, [[William Henry Watson|WH Watson]], a select committee found that Richard's agents' generous hospitality in providing free drinks for the electorate of Kinsale in Kiley's public house amounted to bribery. While Richard was personally exonerated, his election was voided. The committee comprised 3 hostile Liberal MPs and 2 fellow conservatives.<ref>[http://www.dippam.ac.uk/eppi/documents/12215/page/292935 EPPI file on Watson's petition, accessed 1 Sept 2014]</ref> At the next election the Liberal [[Benjamin Hawes]] took the seat by just 3 votes.\n\n==Marriage==\nOn 25 November 1833 in France,<ref>Page 123 of the 1833 Verdun marriage records ''\"Marriages solemnized in the house of his excellency The British Ambassador at the Court of France\"''</ref> Richard married Katherine Frances Jenkinson, a daughter of [[Sir Charles Jenkinson, 10th Baronet]] and his wife Katherine Campbell, a daughter of [[Walter Campbell of Shawfield]]. Sir Charles was a cousin of [[Robert Jenkinson, 2nd Earl of Liverpool|Lord Liverpool]], the [[Prime Minister of the United Kingdom|Prime Minister]] in 1812\u201327.<ref>http://thepeerage.com/p3016.htm#i30160</ref>\n\nThey lived at and rebuilt Deepwell House, [[Blackrock, Dublin]].<ref>[http://www.independent.ie/lifestyle/deepwell-of-laughter-and-tears-29297147.html Deepwell in the Irish Independent, 27 May 2013]</ref> They had a second home at 17 Sillwood Place, [[Brighton]], [[Sussex]].\n\nThey had 8 children, including:\n* Col. Charles WN Guinness CB (1839\u201394)\n* Arthur CCJ Guinness (1841\u201397), who emigrated to [[Melbourne]]\n* Sir Reginald RB Guinness (1842-1909) [[Justice of the peace|JP]], [[Deputy Lieutenant|DL]] for [[County Dublin]]\n* Adelaide (1844-1916) who m. her third cousin [[Edward Guinness, 1st Earl of Iveagh]]\n* Claude HC Guinness (1852\u201395), the managing director of [[Guinness]] 1886-95<ref>[http://www.mocavo.com/Winchester-College-1836-1906-a-Register/735606/225 online dates accessed 1 Sept 2014]</ref>\n\n==In parliament==\nRichard represented 2 divisions in the Parliament of the [[United Kingdom of Great Britain and Ireland]]:\n\n*  [[Kinsale (UK Parliament constituency)]]; 1847 representing the [[Irish Conservative Party]]. His election was voided in 1848.\n*  [[Barnstaple (UK Parliament constituency)]]; 1854-57 representing the [[Conservative Party (UK)]].\n\nRichard died in 1857 aged 60.<ref>Mosley, Charles, editor. Burke's Peerage, Baronetage & Knightage, 107th edition, 3 volumes. Wilmington, Delaware, U.S.A.: Burke's Peerage (Genealogical Books) Ltd, 2003.</ref> His net estate at death was just \u00a3100.<ref>Oxford Dictionary of National Biography, Oxford University Press, 2004; [http://www.oxforddnb.com/view/article/55817 accessed 12 Oct 2014]</ref><ref>Richard Samuel Guinness (1797\u20131857): doi:10.1093/ref:odnb/55817</ref>\n\n==Notes==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Guinness, Richard Samuel}}\n[[Category:Irish barristers]]\n[[Category:Irish lawyers]]\n[[Category:Members of the Parliament of the United Kingdom for County Cork constituencies (1801\u20131922)]]\n[[Category:Irish Conservative Party MPs]]\n[[Category:1797 births]]\n[[Category:1857 deaths]]\n[[Category:Guinness family|Richard Samuel]]\n[[Category:Alumni of King's Inns]]\n[[Category:Conservative Party (UK) MPs for English constituencies]]\n[[Category:Members of the Parliament of the United Kingdom for constituencies in Devon]]\n[[Category:UK MPs 1847\u20131852]]\n[[Category:UK MPs 1852\u20131857]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use dmy dates|date=August 2016}}\n{{Use British English|date=August 2016}}\n'''Richard Samuel Guinness''' (7 June 1797 \u2013 27 August 1857) was an Irish lawyer and a [[Member of parliament#United Kingdom|Member of Parliament]].\n\n==Parents==\nRichard was the son of Richard Guinness (1755-1829), a Dublin barrister and judge, and his wife Mary Darley, descended from a well-known Dublin house-building family. He was a great-nephew of the brewer [[Arthur Guinness]].\n\nHis elder brother [[Robert Rundell Guinness]] (1789-1857) founded the [[Guinness Mahon]] merchant bank in 1836.\n\n==Career==\nRichard was called to the bar at the [[King's Inns]] in [[Dublin]] and practised as a [[barrister]].<ref>Burke, J. ''A Genealogical and Heraldic Dictionary of the Peerage and Baronetage of the British Empire'' (1839, Colburn, London p.645.</ref> He had a banking partnership with his elder brother Robert that ended in the 1830s. He then worked as a land agent, trading as \"R. Guinness & Co.\", but found it difficult in the aftermath of the [[Great Famine (Ireland)|Irish famine]] of the 1840s.\n\nHis election as MP for the [[Kinsale (UK Parliament constituency)|Kinsale division]] ended abruptly in early 1848. On a petition by the losing [[Liberal Party (UK)|Liberal]] candidate, [[William Henry Watson|WH Watson]], a select committee found that Richard's agents' generous hospitality in providing free drinks for the electorate of Kinsale in Kiley's public house amounted to bribery. While Richard was personally exonerated, his election was voided. The committee comprised 3 hostile Liberal MPs and 2 fellow conservatives.<ref>[http://www.dippam.ac.uk/eppi/documents/12215/page/292935 EPPI file on Watson's petition, accessed 1 Sept 2014]</ref> At the next election the Liberal [[Benjamin Hawes]] took the seat by just 3 votes.\n\n==Marriage==\nOn 25 November 1833 in France,<ref>Page 123 of the 1833 Verdun marriage records ''\"Marriages solemnized in the house of his excellency The British Ambassador at the Court of France\"''</ref> Richard married Katherine Frances Jenkinson, a daughter of [[Sir Charles Jenkinson, 10th Baronet]] and his wife Katherine Campbell, a daughter of [[Walter Campbell of Shawfield]]. Sir Charles was a cousin of [[Robert Jenkinson, 2nd Earl of Liverpool|Lord Liverpool]], the [[Prime Minister of the United Kingdom|Prime Minister]] in 1812-27.<ref>http://thepeerage.com/p3016.htm#i30160</ref>\n\nThey lived at and rebuilt Deepwell House, [[Blackrock, Dublin]].<ref>[http://www.independent.ie/lifestyle/deepwell-of-laughter-and-tears-29297147.html Deepwell in the Irish Independent, 27 May 2013]</ref> They had a second home at 17 Sillwood Place, [[Brighton]], [[Sussex]].\n\nThey had 8 children, including:\n* Col. Charles WN Guinness CB (1839\u201394)\n* Arthur CCJ Guinness (1841\u201397), who emigrated to [[Melbourne]]\n* Sir Reginald RB Guinness (1842-1909) [[Justice of the peace|JP]], [[Deputy Lieutenant|DL]] for [[County Dublin]]\n* Adelaide (1844-1916) who m. her third cousin [[Edward Guinness, 1st Earl of Iveagh]]\n* Claude HC Guinness (1852\u201395), the managing director of [[Guinness]] 1886-95<ref>[http://www.mocavo.com/Winchester-College-1836-1906-a-Register/735606/225 online dates accessed 1 Sept 2014]</ref>\n\n==In parliament==\nRichard represented 2 divisions in the Parliament of the [[United Kingdom of Great Britain and Ireland]]:\n\n*  [[Kinsale (UK Parliament constituency)]]; 1847 representing the [[Irish Conservative Party]]. His election was voided in 1848.\n*  [[Barnstaple (UK Parliament constituency)]]; 1854-57 representing the [[Conservative Party (UK)]].\n\nRichard died in 1857 aged 60.<ref>Mosley, Charles, editor. Burke's Peerage, Baronetage & Knightage, 107th edition, 3 volumes. Wilmington, Delaware, U.S.A.: Burke's Peerage (Genealogical Books) Ltd, 2003.</ref> His net estate at death was just \u00a3100.<ref>Oxford Dictionary of National Biography, Oxford University Press, 2004; [http://www.oxforddnb.com/view/article/55817 accessed 12 Oct 2014]</ref><ref>Richard Samuel Guinness (1797\u20131857): doi:10.1093/ref:odnb/55817</ref>\n\n==Notes==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Guinness, Richard Samuel}}\n[[Category:Irish barristers]]\n[[Category:Irish lawyers]]\n[[Category:Members of the Parliament of the United Kingdom for County Cork constituencies (1801\u20131922)]]\n[[Category:Irish Conservative Party MPs]]\n[[Category:1797 births]]\n[[Category:1857 deaths]]\n[[Category:Guinness family|Richard Samuel]]\n[[Category:Alumni of King's Inns]]\n[[Category:Conservative Party (UK) MPs for English constituencies]]\n[[Category:Members of the Parliament of the United Kingdom for constituencies in Devon]]\n[[Category:UK MPs 1847\u20131852]]\n[[Category:UK MPs 1852\u20131857]]\n", "name_user": "Iridescent", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eMarriage:Cleanup andtypo fixing,typo(s) fixed: 1812-27 \u2192 1812\u201327", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Richard_Samuel_Guinness"}
